article.headline: Wyoming 67, Colorado State 61
article.story:
DENVER (AP) -- Ashley Elliott hit six 3-pointers and had 29
points to lead Wyoming over Colorado State 67-61 in the Mountain
West Conference tournament Wednesday, the Cowgirls' first win ever
in a conference tournament.

Kristen Lenhardt added 18 points in fifth-seeded Wyoming's first
win after 14 straight conference tournament losses -- four straight
in the Mountain West.

The Cowgirls (11-17) will face top-seeded New Mexico in the
semifinals Friday, thanks mostly to Elliott's hot shooting early
and late.

Elliott hit four 3-pointers in the first 10 minutes to put
Wyoming up by as much as 14, but the Cowgirls had trouble with
Colorado State's pressure defense in the closing minutes to see the
lead drop to five by halftime.

It was more of the same to start the second.

Fourth-seeded Colorado State (17-11) opened the second half with
a 16-3 run, hounding the Cowgirls into three turnovers and eight
misses in nine shots to take a 41-34 lead.

Wyoming went on a 7-0 run to tie it, but Colorado State answered
with an 8-0 run to go up 51-43.

Then Elliott took over.

She hit a 3-pointer with a hand in her face to cut the lead to
51-48, then tied it with another from the corner on a secondary
break.

Michelle Lieber followed with a layup after Sara Hippen grabbed
an offensive rebound, then Elliott put the Rams up 57-52 on a
three-point play with 3:02 left.

Elliott also added two free throws with a minute left and two
more with 26 seconds left to seal the win, which ended Wyoming's
three-game postseason losing streak against Colorado State. She
finished 6-for-13 on 3-pointers.

Wyoming did a lot of standing around on offense in the first
half, but kept hitting 3-pointers as the shot clock was winding
down.

Elliott opened with a 3-pointer at the shot clock buzzer and
added three more during a 14-1 run that put the Cowgirls up 20-8
with nine minutes left.

Lenhardt was next, hitting consecutive 3-pointers from the wing
that gave Wyoming a 26-12 lead. The Cowgirls were 7-for-13 from
3-point range in the first half, with Elliott connecting on 4 of 6.

Colorado State hit three of its first four shots, then went
cold. The Rams had three turnovers and missed eight straight shots
before Melissa Dennett's putback midway through.

Colorado State got back in it with defense, forcing five
turnovers during a 9-2 run that helped cut Wyoming's lead to 31-25
by halftime.
